From: Bruce Ashfield <bruce.ashfield@gmail.com>
Subject: [PATCH] x86/io_apic: don't panic on missing legacy timer under a hypervisor

check_timer() validates that the legacy 8254 PIT timer interrupt (IRQ0)
can be routed to a CPU through the IO-APIC (or, failing that, the 8259A
PIC, virtual wire, or ExtINT).  It counts PIT ticks via timer_irq_works()
to confirm delivery.

Generation 2 Hyper-V VMs (and other modern virtual platforms) emulate
neither the 8254 PIT nor the 8259 PIC, so IRQ0 never fires and every
routing path check_timer() tries fails:

    ..MP-BIOS bug: 8254 timer not connected to IO-APIC
    ...trying to set up timer (IRQ0) through the 8259A ... failed.
    ...trying to set up timer as Virtual Wire IRQ... failed.
    ...trying to set up timer as ExtINT IRQ... failed :(
    (XEN) *** Panic: IO-APIC + timer doesn't work!

The legacy timer is not required for timekeeping here: under a hypervisor
Xen trusts and uses the local APIC timer in TSC-deadline mode (see
check_deadline_errata() and setup_boot_APIC_clock(), the latter called
immediately after setup_IO_APIC()/check_timer()).  This is exactly how
Linux runs on Hyper-V Generation 2.

When running under a hypervisor, downgrade the fatal panic to a warning
and continue.  This is safe: a platform with a working legacy timer
returns early from check_timer() long before this point, so only guests
that genuinely lack a legacy timer reach here, and for those the local
APIC timer set up next is the intended time source.

Upstream-Status: Pending

Signed-off-by: Bruce Ashfield <bruce.ashfield@gmail.com>
---
 xen/arch/x86/io_apic.c | 18 ++++++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 18 insertions(+)

--- a/xen/arch/x86/io_apic.c
+++ b/xen/arch/x86/io_apic.c
@@ -2005,6 +2005,24 @@
         return;
     }
     printk(" failed :(.\n");
+
+    if ( cpu_has_hypervisor )
+    {
+        /*
+         * Modern hypervisors such as Generation 2 Hyper-V emulate neither
+         * the legacy 8254 PIT nor the 8259 PIC, so there is no IRQ0 timer
+         * interrupt for the routing checks above to validate and they all
+         * fail.  This is not fatal: under a hypervisor the local APIC timer
+         * (TSC-deadline mode) is the real time source and is brought up
+         * immediately afterwards in setup_boot_APIC_clock().  Warn and
+         * continue instead of panicking so Xen can boot as a PIT-less guest.
+         */
+        printk(KERN_WARNING
+               "..no legacy timer interrupt available; "
+               "relying on local APIC timer\n");
+        return;
+    }
+
     panic("IO-APIC + timer doesn't work!  Boot with apic_verbosity=debug and send a report\n");
 }
